&lt;h2 id=&#34;manipulator-kinematics&#34;&gt;Manipulator kinematics
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://Bob-Maxwell.github.io/p/introduction-to-robotics/two-joint-axes1.png&#34;
	width=&#34;1128&#34;
	height=&#34;767&#34;
	srcset=&#34;https://Bob-Maxwell.github.io/p/introduction-to-robotics/two-joint-axes1_hu_3f66e362eefabc0b.png 480w, https://Bob-Maxwell.github.io/p/introduction-to-robotics/two-joint-axes1_hu_e7c23f3cce4b7fa1.png 1024w&#34;
	loading=&#34;lazy&#34;
	
		alt=&#34;The kinematic function of a link is to maintain a fixed relationship between the two joint axes. This relationship can be described with the link length $a$ and twist $\alpha$.&#34;
	
	
		class=&#34;gallery-image&#34; 
		data-flex-grow=&#34;147&#34;
		data-flex-basis=&#34;352px&#34;
	
&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://Bob-Maxwell.github.io/p/introduction-to-robotics/two-joint-axes2.png&#34;
	width=&#34;1343&#34;
	height=&#34;848&#34;
	srcset=&#34;https://Bob-Maxwell.github.io/p/introduction-to-robotics/two-joint-axes2_hu_5d77cd5e4c3bbc7a.png 480w, https://Bob-Maxwell.github.io/p/introduction-to-robotics/two-joint-axes2_hu_cf1edf106b32198.png 1024w&#34;
	loading=&#34;lazy&#34;
	
		alt=&#34;The link offset $d$ and the joint angle $\theta$ are two parameters that may be used to describe the nature of the connection between neighboring links.&#34;
	
	
		class=&#34;gallery-image&#34; 
		data-flex-grow=&#34;158&#34;
		data-flex-basis=&#34;380px&#34;
	
&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We abstract the two rotating cylinder pairs at the end of the connecting rod into two lines, so we only need four parameters to characterize the transformation relationship between the two lines.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;center&gt;
&lt;p&gt;$a_{i-1}$ = the distance from $\hat{Z}_{i-1}$ to $\hat{Z}_i$ measured along $\hat{X}_i$;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;$\alpha_{i-1}$ = the angle from $\hat{Z}_{i-1}$ to $\hat{Z}_i$ measured about $\hat{X}_i$;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;$d_i$ = the distance from $\hat{X}_{i-1}$ to $\hat{X}_i$ measured along $\hat{Z}_i$;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;$\theta_i$ = the angle from $\hat{X}_{i-1}$ to $\hat{X}_i$ measured about $\hat{Z}_i$.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/center&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://Bob-Maxwell.github.io/p/introduction-to-robotics/two-joint-axes3.png&#34;
	width=&#34;1256&#34;
	height=&#34;837&#34;
	srcset=&#34;https://Bob-Maxwell.github.io/p/introduction-to-robotics/two-joint-axes3_hu_389bab2d506fd7e8.png 480w, https://Bob-Maxwell.github.io/p/introduction-to-robotics/two-joint-axes3_hu_e6b57777386a71f7.png 1024w&#34;
	loading=&#34;lazy&#34;
	
		alt=&#34;Link frames are attached so that frame {i} is attached to link i.&#34;
	
	
		class=&#34;gallery-image&#34; 
		data-flex-grow=&#34;150&#34;
		data-flex-basis=&#34;360px&#34;
	
&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://Bob-Maxwell.github.io/p/introduction-to-robotics/two-joint-axes4.png&#34;
	width=&#34;1204&#34;
	height=&#34;811&#34;
	srcset=&#34;https://Bob-Maxwell.github.io/p/introduction-to-robotics/two-joint-axes4_hu_e0e659dfc7ab38b2.png 480w, https://Bob-Maxwell.github.io/p/introduction-to-robotics/two-joint-axes4_hu_804563d33f57fc59.png 1024w&#34;
	loading=&#34;lazy&#34;
	
		alt=&#34;Location of intermediate frames {P}, {Q} and {R}.&#34;
	
	
		class=&#34;gallery-image&#34; 
		data-flex-grow=&#34;148&#34;
		data-flex-basis=&#34;356px&#34;
	
&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;By defining a frame for each link, we have broken the kinematics problem into $n$ subproblems. In order to solve each of these subproblems, namely $T_i^{i-1}$, we will further break each subproblem into four subsubproblems. Each of these four transformations will be a function of one link parameter only and will be simple enough that we can write down its form by inspection, i.e.&lt;/p&gt;
$$
\begin{equation*}
  \begin{aligned}
    P^{i-1} &amp;= T_i^{i-1}~ P^i \\ 
    &amp;= T_R^{i-1}~ T_Q^R~ T_P^Q~ T_i^P~ P^i \\
    &amp;= R_X(\alpha_{i-1})~ D_X(a_{i-1})~ R_Z(\theta_i)~ D_Z(d_i)~ P^i \\
    &amp;= \text{Screw}_X(a_{i-1},\alpha_{i-1})~ \text{Screw}_Z(d_i,\theta_i)~ P^i \\
    &amp;=  \begin{bmatrix}
          1&amp;0&amp;0&amp;a_{i-1}\\
          0&amp;c\alpha_{i-1}&amp;-s\alpha_{i-1}&amp;0\\
          0&amp;s\alpha_{i-1}&amp;c\alpha_{i-1}&amp;0\\
          0&amp;0&amp;0&amp;1\\
        \end{bmatrix}
        \begin{bmatrix}
          c\theta_i&amp;-s\theta_i&amp;0&amp;0\\
          s\theta_i&amp;c\theta_i&amp;0&amp;0\\
          0&amp;0&amp;1&amp;d_i\\
          0&amp;0&amp;0&amp;1\\
        \end{bmatrix}
  \end{aligned}
\end{equation*}
$$&lt;h2 id=&#34;inverse-manipulator-kinematics&#34;&gt;Inverse Manipulator kinematics
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;!-- In this chapter, we investigate the more difficult converse problem: Given the desired position and orientation of the tool relative to the station, how do we compute the set of joint angles which will achieve this desired result? --&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;jacobians-velocities-and-static-forces&#34;&gt;Jacobians: velocities and static forces
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;For linear velocity, assume {$A$} be the fixed frame, {$B$} be the frame attached to a rigid body, and we wish to describe the motion of $^BQ$ relative to frame {$A$}, then&lt;/p&gt;
$$
\begin{equation*}
  \begin{aligned}
    ^AV_Q &amp;= \frac{^A\text{d}}{\text{d}t}(^AX_Q) = \frac{^A\text{d}}{\text{d}t}(^AX_B+^BX_Q) \\
    &amp;= \frac{^A\text{d}}{\text{d}t}(^AX_B) + \frac{^B\text{d}}{\text{d}t}(R_B^A~ ^BX_Q) \\
    &amp;= ^AV_{BORG} + R_B^A~ ^BV_Q
  \end{aligned}
\end{equation*}
